& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Pseudomyxoma peritonei involves the gradual accumulation of gelatinous peritoneal metastases, typically resulting from the rupture of a mucinous appendiceal neoplasm. Standard treatment often includes cytoreductive surgery and hyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy. However, recurrence is common despite optimal cytoreduction, prompting ongoing investigation into novel therapies. This comprehensive review aims to enhance radiologists’ understanding of mucinous appendiceal neoplasms and pseudomyxoma peritonei by focusing on nomenclature, pathophysiology, optimal imaging strategies, and the typical imaging appearance of mucinous appendiceal neoplasm and associated peritoneal disease. It also highlights problematic areas of disease that may affect the ability to achieve complete cytoreduction or influence surgical decision making and includes a surgeon’s perspective on treating this complex condition.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2025</div><div role="paragraph"><i>An earlier incorrect version of this article appeared online. This article was corrected on June 3, 2025.</i></div><div role="paragraph">Supplemental material is available for this article.</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240131">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240131">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Perforated LAMN. (A) Gross specimen shows a dilated appendix (arrow) with periappendiceal mucin (*) following rupture. (B) Gross cut appendix specimen shows the perforation (arrow) and extruded mucin (*)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig1.jpeg" height="884" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Perforated LAMN. <b>(A)</b> Gross specimen shows a dilated appendix (arrow) with periappendiceal mucin (*) following rupture. <b>(B)</b> Gross cut appendix specimen shows the perforation (arrow) and extruded mucin (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows the predictable pathway of ascitic flow (arrows) in an abdomen in which abdominal surgery has not been performed. The peritoneal folds provide structured layers of potential space through which ascites flows. The predictable pathologic spread pattern of tumor cells is called the “redistribution phenomenon.” Gravity facilitates repositories in the most dependent parts of the pelvis, and tumor cells spread cranially by means of the paracolic gutters. There is preferential distribution up the right paracolic gutter to the hemidiaphragm due to the phrenocolic ligament, which prevents mucinous flow to the left hemidiaphragm. (Reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research, all rights reserved.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig2.jpeg" height="1220" width="825" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Illustration shows the predictable pathway of ascitic flow (arrows) in an abdomen in which abdominal surgery has not been performed. The peritoneal folds provide structured layers of potential space through which ascites flows. The predictable pathologic spread pattern of tumor cells is called the “redistribution phenomenon.” Gravity facilitates repositories in the most dependent parts of the pelvis, and tumor cells spread cranially by means of the paracolic gutters. There is preferential distribution up the right paracolic gutter to the hemidiaphragm due to the phrenocolic ligament, which prevents mucinous flow to the left hemidiaphragm. (Reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research, all rights reserved.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Importance of the use of oral contrast material. (A, B) Axial contrast-enhanced CT images without (A) and with (B) positive oral contrast material show increased conspicuity of low-attenuation peritoneal and mesenteric mucinous metastases (arrows). (C) Coronal CT image with intravenous contrast material in a different patient shows an occult fluid-attenuation mesenteric metastasis (arrow), which may have been more conspicuous had positive oral contrast material been administered."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig3.jpeg" height="697" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Importance of the use of oral contrast material. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images without <b>(A)</b> and with <b>(B)</b> positive oral contrast material show increased conspicuity of low-attenuation peritoneal and mesenteric mucinous metastases (arrows). <b>(C)</b> Coronal CT image with intravenous contrast material in a different patient shows an occult fluid-attenuation mesenteric metastasis (arrow), which may have been more conspicuous had positive oral contrast material been administered.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Early versus delayed imaging. Axial early (A) and delayed (B) postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images show the increased conspicuity of the more cellular component of mucinous peritoneal disease (arrow) on the delayed image."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig4.jpeg" height="747" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Early versus delayed imaging. Axial early <b>(A)</b> and delayed <b>(B)</b> postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images show the increased conspicuity of the more cellular component of mucinous peritoneal disease (arrow) on the delayed image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Cellular peritoneal disease. Axial early (A) and delayed (B) phase postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images and axial diffusion-weighted (b = 800 sec/mm2) MR image (C) are shown. The delayed (B) and diffusion-weighted (C) images better show cellular nodular peritoneal metastatic disease invading the bowel (white arrow). Comparison with the apparent diffusion coefficient map (C, inset) is imperative to ensure true diffusion restriction. Fluid in the bowel (black arrow in C, inset) or from mucinous implants can cause T2 shine-through, whereas diffusion-restricted cellular metastases are hypointense (white arrow in C, inset) on the apparent diffusion coefficient map. Mucinous implants may be less invasive and/or more easily peeled off of peritoneal structures than are more cellular tumors."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig5.jpeg" height="657" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Cellular peritoneal disease. Axial early <b>(A)</b> and delayed <b>(B)</b> phase postcontrast fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images and axial diffusion-weighted (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) MR image <b>(C)</b> are shown. The delayed <b>(B)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(C)</b> images better show cellular nodular peritoneal metastatic disease invading the bowel (white arrow). Comparison with the apparent diffusion coefficient map (<b>C</b>, inset) is imperative to ensure true diffusion restriction. Fluid in the bowel (black arrow in <b>C</b>, inset) or from mucinous implants can cause T2 shine-through, whereas diffusion-restricted cellular metastases are hypointense (white arrow in <b>C</b>, inset) on the apparent diffusion coefficient map. Mucinous implants may be less invasive and/or more easily peeled off of peritoneal structures than are more cellular tumors.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="PMP from mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix with signet ring features. (A, B) Contrast-enhanced axial CT (A) and axial T2-weighted MR (B) images show perihepatic low-attenuation and high-signal-intensity material, respectively, without scalloping (white arrow), and soft-tissue attenuation (black arrow in A) and intermediate-signal-intensity plaquelike thickening (black arrow in B) in the hepatorenal space. On CT images, it can be difficult to distinguish among simple ascites, mucinous ascites, and mucinous tissue. (C) Axial delayed gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a moderately thick, mildly irregular, and diffusely enhancing peritoneal tumor (white arrow) in the right upper quadrant and in the hepatorenal space (black arrow). (D) Axial diffusion-weighted MR image shows increased conspicuity of nodular peritoneal (white arrow) and hepatic capsular (black arrow) metastatic disease."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig6.jpeg" height="1396" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. PMP from mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix with signet ring features. <b>(A, B)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT <b>(A)</b> and axial T2-weighted MR <b>(B)</b> images show perihepatic low-attenuation and high-signal-intensity material, respectively, without scalloping (white arrow), and soft-tissue attenuation (black arrow in <b>A</b>) and intermediate-signal-intensity plaquelike thickening (black arrow in <b>B</b>) in the hepatorenal space. On CT images, it can be difficult to distinguish among simple ascites, mucinous ascites, and mucinous tissue. <b>(C)</b> Axial delayed gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a moderately thick, mildly irregular, and diffusely enhancing peritoneal tumor (white arrow) in the right upper quadrant and in the hepatorenal space (black arrow). <b>(D)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image shows increased conspicuity of nodular peritoneal (white arrow) and hepatic capsular (black arrow) metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma in a 70-year-old woman who presented with bloating, abdominal cramping, and upper abdominal discomfort and pressure. She had a slight weight gain over the past year. (A) CT topogram shows curvilinear calcifications (arrows) superimposed over the right iliac crest, which are suggestive of an appendiceal mucocele. (B) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mucocele with extensive PMP (*). Punctate and curvilinear (arrow) calcifications are common. The patient underwent CRS with hyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy for appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma with signet ring features. CRS included evacuation of malignant ascites, right hemicolectomy, diaphragmatic resection, peritonectomy, splenectomy, distal pancreatectomy, hysterectomy, bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy, and extensive pelvic peritonectomies."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig7.jpeg" height="805" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma in a 70-year-old woman who presented with bloating, abdominal cramping, and upper abdominal discomfort and pressure. She had a slight weight gain over the past year. <b>(A)</b> CT topogram shows curvilinear calcifications (arrows) superimposed over the right iliac crest, which are suggestive of an appendiceal mucocele. <b>(B)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mucocele with extensive PMP (*). Punctate and curvilinear (arrow) calcifications are common. The patient underwent CRS with hyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy for appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma with signet ring features. CRS included evacuation of malignant ascites, right hemicolectomy, diaphragmatic resection, peritonectomy, splenectomy, distal pancreatectomy, hysterectomy, bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy, and extensive pelvic peritonectomies.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Appendiceal mucocele in a 61-year-old woman with a right adnexal mass that was incidentally discovered at musculoskeletal pelvic MRI. Endovaginal US image through the structure in the right adnexa shows lamellated intraluminal material (*) characteristic of an appendiceal mucocele. In cross-section (not shown), these concentric layers of echogenic material resemble the appearance of an onion (ie, “onion skin” sign). The right ovary is not visible, likely due to overlying bowel gas and postmenopausal small size. However, despite the right adnexal location, the “gut signature” sign (circle) of alternating hyperechoic and hypoechoic bowel wall layers allowed confirmation of the gastrointestinal origin of this process."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig8.jpeg" height="504" width="1025" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Appendiceal mucocele in a 61-year-old woman with a right adnexal mass that was incidentally discovered at musculoskeletal pelvic MRI. Endovaginal US image through the structure in the right adnexa shows lamellated intraluminal material (*) characteristic of an appendiceal mucocele. In cross-section (not shown), these concentric layers of echogenic material resemble the appearance of an onion (ie, “onion skin” sign). The right ovary is not visible, likely due to overlying bowel gas and postmenopausal small size. However, despite the right adnexal location, the “gut signature” sign (circle) of alternating hyperechoic and hypoechoic bowel wall layers allowed confirmation of the gastrointestinal origin of this process.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Appendiceal mucocele in a 50-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a dilated (&gt;2 cm) appendix (white arrow) with low- or fluid-attenuation intraluminal contents and curvilinear mural calcification (black arrow). Note the lack of mural thickening and periappendiceal inflammatory changes that would be expected for acute appendicitis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig9.jpeg" height="718" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Appendiceal mucocele in a 50-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a dilated (&gt;2 cm) appendix (white arrow) with low- or fluid-attenuation intraluminal contents and curvilinear mural calcification (black arrow). Note the lack of mural thickening and periappendiceal inflammatory changes that would be expected for acute appendicitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Low-grade appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma and PMP in a 42-year-old woman. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a dilated appendix with irregular wall thickening and soft-tissue enhancement (arrow). Subtly enhancing cellular peritoneal disease is also seen (arrowhead) within the mucinous ascites."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig10.jpeg" height="813" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Low-grade appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma and PMP in a 42-year-old woman. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a dilated appendix with irregular wall thickening and soft-tissue enhancement (arrow). Subtly enhancing cellular peritoneal disease is also seen (arrowhead) within the mucinous ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Mucocele in a 61-year-old woman (same patient as in Figure 8) with a right adnexal mass incidentally discovered at musculoskeletal pelvic MRI. Axial T2-weighted MR image with fat saturation (A) and axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image with fat saturation (B) show a markedly dilated appendix filled with T2-hyperintense (arrow in A) nonenhancing (arrow in B) mucinous material. Mucoceles often extend from the right lower quadrant into the right adnexal region and are frequently mistaken for gynecologic abnormalities."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig11.jpeg" height="693" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Mucocele in a 61-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig8">Figure 8</a>) with a right adnexal mass incidentally discovered at musculoskeletal pelvic MRI. Axial T2-weighted MR image with fat saturation <b>(A)</b> and axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image with fat saturation <b>(B)</b> show a markedly dilated appendix filled with T2-hyperintense (arrow in <b>A</b>) nonenhancing (arrow in <b>B</b>) mucinous material. Mucoceles often extend from the right lower quadrant into the right adnexal region and are frequently mistaken for gynecologic abnormalities.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="LAMN in a 67-year-old woman. Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a dilated appendix en fosse (arrow) with extra-appendiceal mucin. At MRI, mucin often appears complex, with lobulations, septa, and/or heterogeneous T2 signal intensity (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig12.jpeg" height="676" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. LAMN in a 67-year-old woman. Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a dilated appendix en fosse (arrow) with extra-appendiceal mucin. At MRI, mucin often appears complex, with lobulations, septa, and/or heterogeneous T2 signal intensity (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="LAMN with appendiceal perforation and periappendiceal spillage of mucin in a 56-year-old woman with acute right lower quadrant pain. (A) Gray-scale US image shows a dilated appendix (*), with discontinuation of the appendiceal wall (arrow) and adjacent complex-appearing fluid (arrowhead). (B) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mucinous ascites (*) that appears more complex on the US image than it does on the CT image. (C) Intraoperative photograph shows mucin filling the intra-abdominal cavity (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig13.jpeg" height="1184" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. LAMN with appendiceal perforation and periappendiceal spillage of mucin in a 56-year-old woman with acute right lower quadrant pain. <b>(A)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a dilated appendix (*), with discontinuation of the appendiceal wall (arrow) and adjacent complex-appearing fluid (arrowhead). <b>(B)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mucinous ascites (*) that appears more complex on the US image than it does on the CT image. <b>(C)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows mucin filling the intra-abdominal cavity (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="CT appearances of peritoneal disease of PMP in different patients with appendiceal mucinous neoplasms. (A) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows scalloping of the hepatic surfaces (arrows). Scalloping can occur along any visceral surface but is most common along hepatic and splenic capsules. (B) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows coarse and curvilinear calcifications within the PMP (arrow). (C) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows serosal implants along the gallbladder (arrowhead). (D) Intraoperative photograph shows omental caking. (E) Axial nonenhanced CT image shows omental caking (asterisk). Early in the disease, the small bowel and its mesentery are often spared, as in this example."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig14.jpeg" height="1296" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. CT appearances of peritoneal disease of PMP in different patients with appendiceal mucinous neoplasms. <b>(A)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows scalloping of the hepatic surfaces (arrows). Scalloping can occur along any visceral surface but is most common along hepatic and splenic capsules. <b>(B)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows coarse and curvilinear calcifications within the PMP (arrow). <b>(C)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows serosal implants along the gallbladder (arrowhead). <b>(D)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows omental caking. <b>(E)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows omental caking (*). Early in the disease, the small bowel and its mesentery are often spared, as in this example.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Known appendiceal mucinous neoplasm in a 60-year-old woman with abdominal pain. (A) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows multifocal small bowel obstruction (arrows). (B) Oblique plane water-soluble fluoroscopic enema image shows strictures throughout the rectum and sigmoid colon (arrows), including severe narrowing of the proximal sigmoid colon (arrowhead). Bowel disease resulting in multiple points of obstruction results in the “chaotic bowel” pattern, characterized by a lack of uniformity in bowel diameter and shape. Patients with invasive bowel disease usually require bowel resection, but multiple segments of involvement and the “chaotic bowel” may preclude the performance of a complete cytoreduction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig15.jpeg" height="655" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Known appendiceal mucinous neoplasm in a 60-year-old woman with abdominal pain. <b>(A)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows multifocal small bowel obstruction (arrows). <b>(B)</b> Oblique plane water-soluble fluoroscopic enema image shows strictures throughout the rectum and sigmoid colon (arrows), including severe narrowing of the proximal sigmoid colon (arrowhead). Bowel disease resulting in multiple points of obstruction results in the “chaotic bowel” pattern, characterized by a lack of uniformity in bowel diameter and shape. Patients with invasive bowel disease usually require bowel resection, but multiple segments of involvement and the “chaotic bowel” may preclude the performance of a complete cytoreduction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Intraoperative photograph shows diffuse miliary disease on the intra-abdominal organs (white arrows) and more plaquelike disease (black arrows) on the parietal peritoneal surface. Miliary disease only occurs in patients with HAMNs and often renders them unresectable, but it is largely occult on images. Because of this, patients with high-grade tumors being considered for CRS often undergo diagnostic laparoscopy to exclude miliary disease or any other unanticipated findings that could preclude them from undergoing surgery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig16.jpeg" height="604" width="1075" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Intraoperative photograph shows diffuse miliary disease on the intra-abdominal organs (white arrows) and more plaquelike disease (black arrows) on the parietal peritoneal surface. Miliary disease only occurs in patients with HAMNs and often renders them unresectable, but it is largely occult on images. Because of this, patients with high-grade tumors being considered for CRS often undergo diagnostic laparoscopy to exclude miliary disease or any other unanticipated findings that could preclude them from undergoing surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Axial CT image shows intraparenchymal metastasis (white arrow), which must be differentiated from peritoneal capsular disease with scalloping (black arrow). Intraparenchymal disease will not be visible at surgery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig17.jpeg" height="900" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Axial CT image shows intraparenchymal metastasis (white arrow), which must be differentiated from peritoneal capsular disease with scalloping (black arrow). Intraparenchymal disease will not be visible at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Extensive small bowel mesenteric involvement of PMP in two patients. (A, B) Axial (A) and coronal (B) contrast-enhanced CT images show extensive sheets of infiltrative metastatic soft tissue involving the leaves of the small bowel mesentery (white arrows) and diffusely involving the small bowel serosa (arrowheads). Also notice diffuse thickening and enhancement of the peritoneum (black arrows) with loculated ascites (*). (C) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a different patient shows more nodular infiltrative disease of the small bowel mesentery (arrows). This nodular appearance has been likened to a “string of pearls.” Extensive small bowel mesenteric involvement usually precludes complete clearing of invasive tumor."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig18.jpeg" height="663" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Extensive small bowel mesenteric involvement of PMP in two patients. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial <b>(A)</b> and coronal <b>(B)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show extensive sheets of infiltrative metastatic soft tissue involving the leaves of the small bowel mesentery (white arrows) and diffusely involving the small bowel serosa (arrowheads). Also notice diffuse thickening and enhancement of the peritoneum (black arrows) with loculated ascites (*). <b>(C)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a different patient shows more nodular infiltrative disease of the small bowel mesentery (arrows). This nodular appearance has been likened to a “string of pearls.” Extensive small bowel mesenteric involvement usually precludes complete clearing of invasive tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Mesenteric foreshortening in a 60-year-old woman. (A) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows substantial ascites (*), but the small bowel floats freely in the peritoneal cavity. (B) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows central clumping of the small bowel due to extensive mesenteric involvement with the tumor (arrows). The bowel is centrally tethered and fixed (ie, “frozen”). This appearance is referred to as mesenteric foreshortening."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig19.jpeg" height="623" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Mesenteric foreshortening in a 60-year-old woman. <b>(A)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows substantial ascites (*), but the small bowel floats freely in the peritoneal cavity. <b>(B)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows central clumping of the small bowel due to extensive mesenteric involvement with the tumor (arrows). The bowel is centrally tethered and fixed (ie, “frozen”). This appearance is referred to as mesenteric foreshortening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="Abdominal cocoon in a 69-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a conglomerate of multiple small bowel loops in the center of the abdomen due to infiltrative metastatic mesenteric disease (white arrows). The clumped bowel is surrounded by loculated ascites and peritoneal thickening (black arrows), an appearance sometimes referred to as “cocoon abdomen.”"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig20.jpeg" height="751" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Abdominal cocoon in a 69-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the abdomen shows a conglomerate of multiple small bowel loops in the center of the abdomen due to infiltrative metastatic mesenteric disease (white arrows). The clumped bowel is surrounded by loculated ascites and peritoneal thickening (black arrows), an appearance sometimes referred to as “cocoon abdomen.”<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="Common and potentially problematic disease sites. (A) Axial CT image with intravenous and oral contrast material shows a dilated proximal stomach (*) secondary to tumor accumulating on the relatively fixed gastric pylorus, antrum, and proximal duodenum (arrow). In such cases of gastric outlet obstruction, partial or near total gastrectomy with reconstruction may be required, increasing the risk for postoperative complications. (B) Axial postcontrast CT image shows extensive disease in the gastrohepatic ligament (*) and involving the porta hepatis, common sites for peritoneal disease. Large-volume tumor in the gastrohepatic ligament may involve the left gastric artery. (C, D) Coronal (C) and axial (D) postcontrast CT images show tumor involvement of the hepatoduodenal ligament in two different patients. Also shown are obstruction of the common duct (upstream dilatation, arrow in C) by metastatic disease and disease encasing and narrowing the main portal vein (arrow in D). Especially in patients with high-grade histologic results, this disease may be difficult to completely resect."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig21.jpeg" height="1358" width="1699" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Common and potentially problematic disease sites. <b>(A)</b> Axial CT image with intravenous and oral contrast material shows a dilated proximal stomach (*) secondary to tumor accumulating on the relatively fixed gastric pylorus, antrum, and proximal duodenum (arrow). In such cases of gastric outlet obstruction, partial or near total gastrectomy with reconstruction may be required, increasing the risk for postoperative complications. <b>(B)</b> Axial postcontrast CT image shows extensive disease in the gastrohepatic ligament (*) and involving the porta hepatis, common sites for peritoneal disease. Large-volume tumor in the gastrohepatic ligament may involve the left gastric artery. <b>(C, D)</b> Coronal <b>(C)</b> and axial <b>(D)</b> postcontrast CT images show tumor involvement of the hepatoduodenal ligament in two different patients. Also shown are obstruction of the common duct (upstream dilatation, arrow in <b>C</b>) by metastatic disease and disease encasing and narrowing the main portal vein (arrow in <b>D</b>). Especially in patients with high-grade histologic results, this disease may be difficult to completely resect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="Metastatic peritoneal mucinous adenocarcinoma of appendiceal origin in a 39-year-old man. Axial postcontrast CT image shows metastatic peritoneal disease (arrow) involving the rectovesical peritoneum and invading the anterior rectal wall and the seminal vesicles (*). This invasion requires seminal vesicle resection for complete cytoreduction, rendering ejaculation impossible in the postoperative setting."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig22.jpeg" height="582" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Metastatic peritoneal mucinous adenocarcinoma of appendiceal origin in a 39-year-old man. Axial postcontrast CT image shows metastatic peritoneal disease (arrow) involving the rectovesical peritoneum and invading the anterior rectal wall and the seminal vesicles (*). This invasion requires seminal vesicle resection for complete cytoreduction, rendering ejaculation impossible in the postoperative setting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="High-grade and low-grade appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma in two patients. (A, B) High-grade appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma in an 80-year-old man. Axial CT images acquired with intravenous and oral contrast agents show a large appendiceal mucocele (* in A), with rupture. Note the mural calcifications (arrowhead in A). The mucin has invaded into the retroperitoneal iliopsoas muscle (arrow in A and B, main image). This infiltrative retroperitoneal disease is difficult to eradicate surgically. Mucin infiltrating down posterior to the iliopsoas muscle was not completely resected (arrow in inset, B). (C) Low-grade mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 34-year-old man. Axial postcontrast CT image shows bilateral pelvicaliectasis (arrows) with delayed nephrogram on the right (*) secondary to retroperitoneal invasion with involvement of the ureters. A right ureteral stent is partially visualized but is malfunctioning. Complete resection without ureteral resection or ureteronephrectomy is difficult."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240131/asset/images/large/rg.240131.fig23.jpeg" height="1364" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. High-grade and low-grade appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma in two patients. <b>(A, B)</b> High-grade appendiceal mucinous adenocarcinoma in an 80-year-old man. Axial CT images acquired with intravenous and oral contrast agents show a large appendiceal mucocele (* in <b>A</b>), with rupture. Note the mural calcifications (arrowhead in <b>A</b>). The mucin has invaded into the retroperitoneal iliopsoas muscle (arrow in <b>A</b> and <b>B</b>, main image). This infiltrative retroperitoneal disease is difficult to eradicate surgically. Mucin infiltrating down posterior to the iliopsoas muscle was not completely resected (arrow in inset, <b>B</b>). <b>(C)</b> Low-grade mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 34-year-old man. Axial postcontrast CT image shows bilateral pelvicaliectasis (arrows) with delayed nephrogram on the right (*) secondary to retroperitoneal invasion with involvement of the ureters. A right ureteral stent is partially visualized but is malfunctioning. Complete resection without ureteral resection or ureteronephrectomy is difficult.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240131&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Young RH, Gilks CB, Scully RE. Mucinous tumors of the appendix associated with mucinous tumors of the ovary and pseudomyxoma peritonei. A clinicopathological analysis of 22 cases supporting an origin in the appendix. <em>Am J Surg Pathol</em> 1991;15(5):415–429.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/00000478-199105000-00001">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2035736/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Mucinous+tumors+of+the+appendix+associated+with+mucinous+tumors+of+the+ovary+and+pseudomyxoma+peritonei.+A+clinicopathological+analysis+of+22+cases+supporting+an+origin+in+the+appendix&amp;author=RH+Young&amp;author=CB+Gilks&amp;author=RE+Scully&amp;publication_year=1991&amp;journal=Am+J+Surg+Pathol&amp;pages=415-429&amp;doi=10.1097%2F00000478-199105000-00001&amp;pmid=2035736">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Carr NJ, Cecil TD, Mohamed F, et al; Peritoneal Surface Oncology Group International. A Consensus for Classification and Pathologic Reporting of Pseudomyxoma Peritonei and Associated Appendiceal Neoplasia: The Results of the Peritoneal Surface Oncology Group International (PSOGI) Modified Delphi Process. <em>Am J Surg Pathol</em> 2016;40(1):14–26.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/PAS.0000000000000535">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26492181/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=A+Consensus+for+Classification+and+Pathologic+Reporting+of+Pseudomyxoma+Peritonei+and+Associated+Appendiceal+Neoplasia%3A+The+Results+of+the+Peritoneal+Surface+Oncology+Group+International+%28PSOGI%29+Modified+Delphi+Process&amp;author=NJ+Carr&amp;author=TD+Cecil&amp;author=F+Mohamed&amp;author=Peritoneal+Surface+Oncology+Group+International&amp;publication_year=2016&amp;journal=Am+J+Surg+Pathol&amp;pages=14-26&amp;doi=10.1097%2FPAS.0000000000000535&amp;pmid=26492181">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Digestive System Tumours. WHO Classification of Tumours. 5th ed. Lyon, France: World Health Organization, 2019.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=WHO+Classification+of+Tumours&amp;author=Digestive+System+Tumours&amp;publication_year=2019">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Egner JR. AJCC Cancer Staging Manual. <em>JAMA</em> 2010;304(15):1726–1727.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2010.1525">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=AJCC+Cancer+Staging+Manual&amp;author=JR+Egner&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=JAMA&amp;pages=1726-1727&amp;doi=10.1001%2Fjama.2010.1525">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">5.</div><div id="r5" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">AJCC Cancer Staging System. Appendix, Version 9: American College of Surgeons. <em>ACS</em>, 2022.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=AJCC+Cancer+Staging+System.+Appendix%2C+Version+9%3A+American+College+of+Surgeons&amp;publication_year=2022&amp;journal=ACS">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">6.</div><div id="r6" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Marmor S, Portschy PR, Tuttle TM, Virnig BA. The rise in appendiceal cancer incidence: 2000-2009. <em>J Gastrointest Surg</em> 2015;19(4):743–750.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11605-014-2726-7">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25560182/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+rise+in+appendiceal+cancer+incidence%3A+2000-2009&amp;author=S+Marmor&amp;author=PR+Portschy&amp;author=TM+Tuttle&amp;author=BA+Virnig&amp;publication_year=2015&amp;journal=J+Gastrointest+Surg&amp;pages=743-750&amp;doi=10.1007%2Fs11605-014-2726-7&amp;pmid=25560182">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">7.</div><div id="r7" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lin YL, Xu DZ, Li XB, et al. Consensuses and controversies on pseudomyxoma peritonei: a review of the published consensus statements and guidelines. <em>Orphanet J Rare Dis</em> 2021;16(1):85.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13023-021-01723-6">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33581733/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Consensuses+and+controversies+on+pseudomyxoma+peritonei%3A+a+review+of+the+published+consensus+statements+and+guidelines&amp;author=YL+Lin&amp;author=DZ+Xu&amp;author=XB+Li&amp;publication_year=2021&amp;journal=Orphanet+J+Rare+Dis&amp;pages=85&amp;doi=10.1186%2Fs13023-021-01723-6&amp;pmid=33581733">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">8.</div><div id="r8" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Asare EA, Compton CC, Hanna NN, et al. The impact of stage, grade, and mucinous histology on the efficacy of systemic chemotherapy in adenocarcinomas of the appendix: Analysis of the National Cancer Data Base. <em>Cancer</em> 2016;122(2):213–221.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/cncr.29744">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26506400/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+impact+of+stage%2C+grade%2C+and+mucinous+histology+on+th